close_symbols: Callback function-pointer typedef used when OS_CleanUpObject is registered (the iterator/callback signature)
All call sites or registration functions that invoke or register OS_CleanUpObject
explanation:
- uint32: needed to know the exact underlying type and qualifiers (e.g. typedef to uint32_t or a qualifiable type) so we can determine whether the pointed-to object is mutable and whether a const qualification would be appropriate.
- osal_id_t: needed to determine whether object_id is an integer or pointer type (and thus whether any const-related requirements apply to that parameter). Although object_id is passed by value here, its type affects API expectations and whether const should be applied elsewhere.
- OS_CleanUpObject (declaration/prototype in public header): the header declaration may contain different qualifiers than the definition (e.g. const on the parameter or different pointer types). We must compare the definition to the declared prototype to decide if a const qualification would be compatible or required by the API.
- Callback function-pointer typedef used when OS_CleanUpObject is registered (the iterator/callback signature): this typedef determines whether the callback API requires a void *arg or a const void *arg. If the API expects a non-const void * then OS_CleanUpObject cannot use a const-qualified pointer; if the API expects const void * then the definition may violate the prototype or the API intent.
- All call sites or registration functions that invoke or register OS_CleanUpObject: examining callers (or places that pass the arg value) shows what actual objects are passed as arg (read-only data vs writable counters) and whether callers pass const-qualified pointers. This is necessary to decide if making the pointer-to-data const is feasible without breaking callers or modifying behavior.
